{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_arguingmatch_ver02/data/sn96060765/00383341917/1923092101/0489.xml":{"full_text":"I\nCHURCH OF LATTER HAY SAINTS, HOLBROOK\nCOOLEY LUMBER COMPANY\nC. P. Cooley, Prop.\nWith the purchase by the Cooley\nLumber Company of the interests of\nthe Hall Lumber Company of Hol\nbrook in August of this year, this\nCity may now boast of the largest\nretail lumber organization in North\nern Arizona. The establishment of\nthe Cooley Lumber Company dates\nback to 1916. when at that time the\nnew organization bought out the Car\nbon City Lumber Company here. The\nbusiness has been under the same\nadministration since establishment.\nMr. C. P. Cooley, under whose sole\nownership and management the busi\nness is conducted, is a native of Ari\nzona and was born and raised in\nNavajo County. Mr. Cooley was for\nmerly engaged in the livestock busi\nness of this section, and his family\nis one of the most prominent in this\npart of the State. The town of Cool\ney, Arizona, was named after his fath\ner. Mr. Cooley devotes all of his\ntime to the business, is a member of\nthe local Chamber of Commerce, and\nis a fraternal man. He is also a\nmember and a Director in the local\nRotary Club.\nSummed up tersely, the Cooley\nLumber Company handles at whole\nsale and retail, a complete stock of\neverything to be used in the con\nstruction of a modern building. Trade\nterritory extends one hundred miles\nnorth and south from Holbrook and\nto intermediate points on the east.\nBoth native and coast lumber is\nhandled, Bradley Vrooman paints,\nBeaver Board products, and the Com\npany has the official agency here for\nthe American Block Coal mining at\nGallup, New Mexico.\nThe main yard is 150x100 feet in\nground space and there is a platform\nand two warehouses, one 25x60 feet\nand. one 25x40 feet maintained on\ntrackage. The second yard is also\n100x150 feet in ground space. Local\ndelivery is maintained and the \u2018phone\nnumber is 119. The business has\nshown a most satisfactory growth,\nand the Rotary Code of Ethics has\nbeen stressed in the business policy.\nMr. Cooley is a booster and a firm\nbeliever in the future of Holbrook\nHe said: \"I can only say one thing\u2014\nthat the future outlook is very good,\neven discounting the possibilities of\noil. Range conditions are good, and\nalso general prospects. We need a\nhotel.\u201d\nSHADES OF ISAAK WALTON!\nJENNINGS AUTOMOBILE COMPANY\n(Continued from page one)\ndent of Arizona, at intervals, since\n1906. He was formerly Supervisor of\nthe Sitgreaves National Forest for a\nperiod of six years. He is a native\nof Detroit, Michigan, and was form\nerly with the Detroit Edison Company\nfor four years in their electrical en\ngineering department before coming\nWest. Mr. Jennings also was con\nnected with the Reclamation Service.\nHe devotes his entire time to the\nbusiness at present, and is serving\nhis first term as a member of the\nCity Council. Mr. Jennings is a mem- i\nber of the local Chamber of Commerce\nand a Fraternal man. Connected\nwith him is Mr. J. C. McCleve, book\nkeeper. and Mr. John H. Miller, shop\nforeman.\nThe Jennings Automobile Company\nnow handles exclusively Dodge Broth\ners Motor Vehicles for Navajo and\nApache Counties, and originally took\nover the agency in the Fall of 1922.\nAll business is handled out of this\noffice, and the Company has an an\nnual contract for 50 cars. Mr. Jen\nnings states that the Touring Car is\nthe most popular in sales in his ter\nritory, but that he is selling quite a\nfew Commercial Cars. This is the\nfirst active agency established here\nand at present there is/@.pproximately\n110 Dodge Brothers iuotor Vehicles\nin use in the territory the Company\nBUTTERFLY DANCE OF TIIF HOPI INDIANS\nserves. The Company also handles\nSales and Service for the same ter\nritory for Graham Brothers Trucks.\nThe company handles Goodyear\ntires exclusively, and will establish in\nthe near future a complete battery\ndepartment, handling some well\nknown battery. A general line of\noverhauling and repairing is done,\nand a commercial storage capacity of\n30 cars had. The building occupied\nis of concrete, with fire walls and ce\nment floor throughout. Floor space\nutilized is 50x150 feet, and Mr. Jen\nnings also owns adjacent property,\nwhich he will utilize soon for a free\ncamp ground. The location of the\nJennings Automobile Company is on\nPorter Street, at the junction of the\nGallup and Springerville branches of\nthe National Old Trails Highway.\nThe \u2018phone number is 71, and the\nplace is open from: early in the morn\ning until late at night. A road ser\nvice car is maintained, and general\ninformation dispensed to tourists.\nPilling station service is rendered,\nand the company handles the Stand\nard Oil line in this department.\nThe growth in business has been\nsteady,- and the management endea\nvors to give service at fair prices.\nMr. Jennings is a booster, and said:\n\u201ci look for a steady and continued\ngi owth in this section, regardless of\nwhether we strike oil. This town\nhas advanced wonderfully in the last\nfew years. The tourist business is\nincreasing 50% to 80% every year.\nWe need the development of some\nof our now dormant resources.\nHOLBROOK LIGHT AND POWER\nCOMPANY\nLight, Power and Ice\nA clean-cut example of the irre\nprochable service a rightly conducted\nand managed public utility can offer\nto the community in which it oper\nates is had in the above concern.\nThe Holbrook Eight and Power Com\npany was organized in 1913, and the\nplant was built in 1915. Mr. Ken\nneth H. Myers, under whose personal\ndirection the business is conducted,\nhas been a resident of Arizona since\n1918 and is a native of Ohio. Mr Myers\nentire experience has been along\nelectrical lines, both from practical\nand executive standpoints. At the\npresent time he devotes his entire\nattention to the business. He is an\nofficer and director of the Arizona\nState Bank at Winslow, and a mem\nber of the local Rotary Club and\nChamber of Commerce. Mr. J. T.\nBaird is Plant Superinten 'ent and\nhas been connected with the Com\npany since 1915.\nThe Holbrook Light and Power\nCompany furnshes light, power, and\nice to the city of Holbrook, serving\nabout 300 customers with light. The\ndistribution system embraces about\nthirty miles of wiring. The plant is\nof the one unit type and has a capa\nj city of 100 kilow-atts, power being\ndeveloped from ,a Semi-Diesel En\ngine. Twenty-four hour per day ser-\nI vice is rendered. The Company\nhandles a complete line of all stand\nard electrical appliances and fixtures\nand does all of the local electrical\nj contracting here. Tiie Company also\nfurnishes power for the local water\nand sewer system. The ice-plant\nhas a ten ton capacity, and all ice\ni is made from distilled water. Local\ndelivery is maintained and the Com\npany does quite a bit of shipping ir\nthe ice department bv truck through\nthe southern part of this district. The\n-1 Holbrook Light and Power Company\nis so excellently equipped that it\ncould furnish electrical energy to\na town of twice the population o\nHolbrook. The plant is located on\nthe east side of town and directly on\ntrackage, the Company owing its own\nspur-track. Ground space utilized\nHolbrook\u2014Continued\nNAVAJO GARAGE CO., INI.\n(Continued from page one)\nthe Company. The essential princi\nples embodied in the business policy\nupon which the Company was found\ned, and- is being conducted, are that\nall customers must be thoroughly sat\nisfied, and that all workmanship is\naccompanied by a strict guarantee\nThis is adhered to with almost re;\ngious fidelity.\nAll three active members of the\nCompany are ardent boosters for this\nsection of the State, and are sincere\nbelievers in the future development\nof this City and its environs. Mr.\nPatterson said: \u201cI believe the future\nwill show a steadily increasing busi\nness year by year, regardless of\nwhether oil is developed or not. This\ntown has always shown a steady\ngrowth, and there is every indication\nat present that it will continue to do\nso in the future. AVe need the im\nprovement cff Porter Street, which\nleads from the Santa Fe Station past\nthe Court House, and over which\nGallup and Springerville travel along\nthe Old Trails Highway must pass.\"\no\nL. B. PUTNEY MERCANTILE CO.\nWholesale Grocers\nThe name \u201cPutney\u201d has been known\nfor a period of years throughout this\nsection of Arizona and the adjacent\npart of New' Mexico as representing\nintegrity in business, a desire to\nserve the community, and a constant\nendeavor to cafry on hand a com\nplete stock of all articles for the\nneeds and wants of the wholesale\ngrocery buying public. Under the\ncareful guidance of Mr. \\V. H. Cham\nberlain this company here has built\nup a most enviable reputation for\n\u201cpush\u201d, \u201chustle\u201d, and \u201caggressive\nness,\u201d and \u201cbillboards\u201d service in\nevery transaction.\nThe L. B. Putney Mercantile Com\npany was first established here in\n1915 as a branch of the company of\nthe same name in Albuquerque, New\nMexico. In 1917 it was incorporated\nas a separate institution, but retain\ning the same name for the cumula\ntive publicity value. Mr. W. H.\nChamberlain, under whose active\nmanagement the business is conduct\ned, first came to Arizona in 1895, but\nhis last continuous residency dates\nfrom the first part of 1915. Mr.\nChamberlain is a native of Tennessee,\nand was formerly connected with the\nPutney interests in Albuquerque for\na period of eighteen years, winning\nhis way upward, step by step. Mr.\nChamberlain at present devotes his\nentire time in his managerial capa\ncity here, and was formerly a mem\nber of the City Council and President\nof the Chamber of Commerce. At\npresent Mr. Chamberlin is President\nof the local School Board. Connect\ned with him here is Mr. H. E. Jen\nsen, Assistant Manager, and Mr. F.\nE. Johnson, Head Salesman.\nThe L. B. Putney Mercantile Com\npany handles at wholesale, exclus\nively, a complete line of groceries and\nproduce, wool, hides, peltts and Nav\najo blankets. This firm is the pio\nneer exclusive wholesale grocery\nhouse in Northern Arizona. This is\ntrue too, of the Putney house at Albu\nquerque, which was opened in 1878\nbefore the coming of the railway to\nthat city. The house handles only\nstandard, nationally-advertised pro\nducts throughout, and buys all pro\nduce from the surrounding country\nside. In fact, the Putney Company\nhandles, as nearly as possible, only\nArizona raised products.\nThe trade territory extends west\nto Ash Fork and including Winslow,\nFlagstaff. Williams and the Grand\nCanyon, east to Gallup, New Mexico,\nand including the Hopi and Navajo\nIndian Reservations, and south to\nFort Apache and Springerville. In\nfact, it ma be said that the circle\nthat is made by the Company\u2019s rej>-\nresentative in a car shows a total of\n870 miles around the circuit. Pro\nducts are handled by trucks north\nand south, and by the railroad east\nand west, for distribution. The busi\nness here has shown a remarkable\ngrowth, which is borne out by the\nfact that the original floor space was\n30x80 and today the main house is\n50x300 feet, together with a basement\n50x100 feet, and a modernly construct\ned brick warehouse with a sto\nrage capacity of sixty cars. The lo\ncation is directly on trackage.\nService and quality have been the\npredominating factors in the code of\nethics employed by the management.\nLocal delivery is made and the \u2018phone\nnumber is 88. The entire personnel\nof the company are strong believers\nin the ultimate growth and expan\nsion of the Holbrook trade territory.\nThey all wish to be quoted as boost\ners, and Mr. Chamberlin said: \u201cThe\nfuture looks very good. I feel very\noptimistic over Holbrook and its ter\nritory. I believe we are just begin\nning to grow, and I think this is\ntrue, too, of all of Northern Arizona.\nThe cattle and sheep industries are\nshowing improvement, and the range\nconditions are better than they have\nbeen in eight years. Also the oil\ncompanies are spending money for\ndevelopment purposes, have passed\nthe speculative stages, and are now\nactively engaged in drilling. AVe need\ncivic improvements, and better co\noperation among all interests, and\nabove all, the spirit of progressive\nness that insures the expansion of\nall communities.\nis 260x100 feet and the telephone\nnumber is 99.\n\u201cUninterrupted service\u201d is the\nadmirable slogan of the Company,\nand that it is strictly adhered to is\nshown by the fact that during the\nlast three months the total time of\ninvoluntary interrupted service was\nten minutes. An average of six peo\nple are employed. The Company is\nmaking improvements as fast as pos\nsible, and the oil engine now- used\nwas installed last November. It is\nthe intention of the management to\neventually install a second oil engine\nand to discontinue the use of steam\naltogether.\nMr. Alyers is a firm believer in the\nfuture of Holbrook, is a booster and\nsaid: \u201cHolbrook is coming back\nOur business indicates an improve\nment during the latter part of 1922\nand all of 1923. AATiat we need here\nis the establishment of some enter\nprise which w-ill utilize our natural\nresources or products, and expend a\nregular pay-roll.\u201d\nTHE WINSLOW MAIL\nMERCHANT STOUKGROAVERS\nBANK\n(Continued from page one)\nness break-down. In January 1921,\nMr. Moritz became connected with j\nthe State Banking Department and\nserved as Chief Examiner until April j\n1922. From 1910 until 1916. Mr. j\nMoritz was connected with the First\nNational Bank at Albuquerque. New\nMexico. He is a native of Mississippi j\nand altogether has had thirteen years\nbanking experience. Mr. Moritz de- j\nvotes his entire time to the bank\u2019s;\naffairs in his administrative capacity I\nHe is a member of th local Rotary!\nClub and a Fraternal man. Mr. Mor\nitz is not only considered a capable!\nbanker, but he is also an indivdual j\nwho possesses a rather unusually;\ngood personality and an inherent j\nspirit of good-fellowship.\nThe Merchants and Stockgrowers;\nBank conducts a general banking\nbusiness in all its branches and holds\nmembership in both the State and\nNational Associations. Safety depos- j\nit boxes are maintained for the con-!\nvenience of customers, and five perj\nceht is paid on time deposits. Bank\ning service is rendered within a ra\ndius of one hundred miles surround\ning Holbrook and this institution is\nconceded to be the oldest, largest,\nand strongest bank within this trade\nterritory. One of the strong points\nbehind the Merchants and Stock\ngrowers Bank is the enormous wealth\nbehind it. It is estimated that this\ncollective wealth, taken individually\napart from the bank itself, is conser-'\nvatively estimated at a million dol\nlars. The present capital of the bank\nis $100,000.00, with surplus and undi\nvided profits of about $40,000.00. De\nposits at present are running about I\n$600,000.00 and have touched $722,-!\n000.00 at high water mark. This j\nshowing is almost phenomenal, con I\nsidering circumstances as they exist- j\ned then and now, and also taking into\nconsideration the difference in local j\nconditions.\nThe grow-th in volume of business\naccorded the Merchants and Stock- j\ngrowlers Bank certifies to the faith;\nthe banking public have in this insti- j\ntution, and also pays a distinct com- j\npliment to the administrative person- i\nnel. All members of the bank have;\nat heart the best interests of the j\ncommunity always, and the plane j\nupon which the bank is operated is I\nmuch higher than that of the mere'\ndollars and cents hanking business, j\nAlong this line Active Vice-President j\nMoritz said: \u201cMy personal idea of\nwhat part a bank should play in the\ndevelopment of the community it\nserves is that it should endeavor at\nall times to serve unselfishly that\ncommunity to the complete satis\nfaction of its customers. No bank\nis thoroughly fulfilling its mission\nunless it aids and helps in numerous\ncivic advancements and enterprises;\nwhich do not directly contribute to the j\nwealth of its stockholders. The\nbanking business is essentially one of!\nservice, first, last and always.\u201d\nThe Merchants and Stockgrowers j\nBank is esentially a home-owned and!\nhome-operated institution. All of its\nofficers and directors are, without ex-|\nception, men who have made indivi-j\ndual successes in their chosen careers I\nThen. too. another of the many strong\npoints of this Bank is the fact that\nthe average age of residency and\nactivity of its directing personnel, in j\nthis part of Arizona, approximatesj\nforty years. The bank owns its own j\nhome, both here and at St. Johns. The j\nbuilding occupied here is in the heart\nof the business district, is of stone\nconstruction, and the banking room\nfloor space is 35x150 feet. All mo\ndern conveniences for the expediting\nof daily business and for the protec\ntion of its clients\u2019 affairs have been\ninstalled.\nThe entire personnel of the Mer\nchants and Stockgrow r ers Bank are\nalways ready and willing to do their\nfull share in anything for the better\nment of Holbrook and this section of\nArizona, and wish to he quoted as\nboosters. Active Vice-President\nMoritz said: \u201cI believe we have a\nwonderful future here. I think the\nstock industry will show a continued\nimprovement, and after all, this is\nprobably the basic industry of this\ndistrict, and, as it develops, so will\nthis section develop. AA T e need closer;\nco-operation between the business j\nhouses and our various industries.\u201d j\no\nHOLBROOK INSURANCE AGENCY\n\u201cInsurance Service\u201d\nLloyd Henning, Mgr.\nThe activities and successes of ex\nclusive insurance agencies are in a\ngreat manner indicative of, and play\na most vital part in, the stability and\nexpansion of any community. Stand\ning alone in their given line in North\nern Arizona, and ranking among thej\nforemost of dependable exclusive in\nsurance agencies in the entire State,\nis the above concern, established here\nunder its present management a lit\ntle over one year. However, Mr.\nLloyd C. Henning, under whose active\nmanagement the business is conduc:-\ned, has been in the insurance busi- j\nness here for about ten years. Mr.\nHenning has been a resident of Ari\nzona since 1897, and is a native of\nIllinois. The majority of his exper\nience has been in the newspaper busi\nness, in banking and in insurance.\nHe was formerly connected with\npublications both here, and a* AA\u2019in- 1\nslow and St. Johns. Mr. Helming is)\nClerk of the Superior Court here.\nMayor of Holbrook, Pres: uni of thej\nRotary Club. Cashier and Director of\nthe First National Bank, a Director;\nof the Chamber of Commerce, and is 1\na fraternal man, being at present j\nState Junior Grand Deacon of the j\nMasonic Order.\nMr. Henning handles all classes of\n'insurance, excepting life, and rep-1\nresenting altogether some forty odd\ncompanies. All companies handled;\nare standard old-line companies, no j\nmutuals, and including some of the!\nlargest companies in the world.;\nAmong some of the largest hand\nled are. for fire insurance. Home, j\nRoyal, and Aetna: for surety and\nbonding. National Surety Company j\nand Maryland Casualty Company for j\nautomobile and plate glass. New- j\nA\u2019ork. This is the only exclusive in-1\nsurance agency in Northern Arizona j\nalong the Santa Fe Railw-ay. and the\ntei ritory embraced covers all of Apa- j\nche and Navajo Counties and their\nadjacent trade territories. Mr. Hen-\n\u25a0v^x 1 v 1 /yflWwf Ki\nWILD TERREY FOR THANKSGIVING DINNER\nNAVA JO-APACHE ABSTRACT AND\nTITLE COMPANY\nH. D. Lore, Mgr.\nThere is in existence no business 1\ntoday that calls for as careful atten- j\ntion to details as does the abstract\ning business. The slogan \u201cdown-to\nthe-minute\u201d was most certainly born\nin an abstract office. An abstract!\ncompany that measures up to every j\nprinciple set for the 1923 demand, is\nthe above concern, established here\nfive years ago under the present ad\nministration. Mr. H. D. Lore, under\nwhose active management the busi\nness is conducted, has been a resi\ndent of Arizona the past sixteen\nyears, and is a native of Pennsyl\nvania. A majority of his experience\nhas been along the lines of mining,\nreclamation and abstracting. Mr.\nLore has had twenty-five years' ex\nperience with real estate, from some\nangle of the business, and altogether!\nhas spent sixteen years in the abs-!\ntracting business in Arizona.\nThe Navajo-Apache Abstract and!\nTitle Company does a complete line!\nof abstracting, and handles real j\nestate and fire insurance. This is I\nthe only official abstracting company!\nfor Navajo and Apache Counties, and\na complete set of records is kept\nshowing the transcript of every piece\nof real estate in the two counties\nsince they were organized, and dating\nback to the original patents or rail\nway grants in 1863. The company is\nlisted nationally, and Mr. Lore is a\nmember of the American Association\nof Title Men. All abstracts are made\nin duplicate, are certified to, indexed\nthroughout, and the different records\nkept in logical squence, and in fact,\neverything done to clarify and ex\npedite legal examination by attor\nneys. All abstracts from this com\npany are accepted as evidence of\ntitle by examining attorneys and by\nthe Federal Land Bank. The com\npany has utilized the entire five\nyears of its existence in establishing\none of the finest and most modern\noffices in the entire State. Along\nthis line it may be well to mention\nthat this company made the largest\nand most complete abstract ever\nmade in the State of Arizona. This\nabstract was for the Aztec Land and\nCattle Company and consisted of!\n243 sheets, 17x22 inches in size. The!\nunexcelled work rendered by this\ncompany has been responsible, to a j\ngreat degree, for the amount of money:\nloaned by the Federal Land Bank in'\nthis vicinity, which runs well into)\nthe hundred thousands. All banks j\nin this district are customers of this j\ncompany, and Mr. Lore states that i\nthe Federal Government form is used\nthroughout \u2022in the abstract depart\nment. The company has the follow\ning departments: Legal. Abstract,\nCivil Engineering, Blue Printing,\nContracting, Leasing. And the busi\nness consists of abstracts, certifi\ncates of title, personal searches,\nescrow agents, maps and mapping,\nand oil leases. Mr. Lore is still in\nterested in the possibilities of irriga-j\ntion in this surrounding section.\nMr. Lore is a booster, and said: j\n\u201cWe extend 1 an invitation to the world\nto come to Holbrook. If your coming j\nto us is of your own volition; if your\nbusiness is able to stand alone, make\nmoney for yourself and us, we want\nyou. No political nor business combi-1\nnation, nor other handicap will con-i\nfront you here. You will have keen\ncompetition, naturally, but any dis- j\ntrict without competition is a dead\none. We urge you to make a per-|\nsonal investigation of opportunities j\nhere, before reaching a definite decis-j\nion. We need CAPITAL in Hol\nbrook and Navaio County, and MEN\nwith energy and practical knowledge\nthat will make that capital work.\u201d\nning\u2019s Agency does quite a bit of\nautomobile insurance, and also a 1\nlarge business in atuomobile financ\ning. representing for this the Com\nmercial Sureties Corporation.\n\u201cInsurance Service\u2019 is the motto\nof the -Holbrook Insurance Agenc\nand it is strictly adhered to at all j\ntimes. The business has shown a l\nsteady growth, and Mr. Henning is;\ncontinually endeavoring to give \u201cmore'\nservice\u201d. He states that Holbrook is i\nvery well protected by insurance,\nand especially so in the matter of;\nfire insurance. Mr. Henning is one\nof the constructive business citizens\nof this community, takes an active\npart in all civic enterprises, and is aj\nbooster. He said: \u201cThe first thing\nthat must occur in order to bring a\nfull return of prosperity to this sec\ntion, must be a \u201ccome back\u201d of the\ncattle and sheep industries. In or\nder for this condition to be fu 1 filled\nwe must have favorable market and\nweather conditions. We need paved\nstreets, and protection from the\nwearing away of the banks o' the\nLittle Colorado River here.\u201d\nv\n\n_2_\nWA.IO GARAGE, HOLBROOK t a\nLOIIS MARLEAU, LAPIDARIST\n\u201cPetrified Wood Jewelry\u2014The\nGift Unique*\u2019\nTn this naturally wonderful South\nwestern country of ours it is not un\nusual for this section to attract to it\nartists from everywhere. Louis Mar\nleau, lapidarist, comes under this\nhead, and this city, and the entire\nState of Arizona, is complimented by\nhis being in business here. Very\nseldom indeed would one find such a\nhighly specialized technician and ar\ntist as is Mr. Marleau in a city of\nless than one-half million inhabi\ntants. In the cutting of fine stones\na circle is known as a \u201clap\u201d, hence\nthe shop where this is done is known\nas a lapidary, and the one who does\nthis exquisite work, or the artist, is\nknown as the lapidarist. Mr. Mar\nleau came here for his health, which\nhas shown a decided improvement,\nbut aside from this fact, he, like all\ntrue artists, has made a wonderful\nsuccess, for in this modern day and\nage of high specialization and keen\ncompetition, the world bows down to\n\u201cthe man who knows\u201d. And that Mr.\nMarleau does know is shown by the\nfact that he has had twenty-eight\nconsecutive years of experience in the\nhighly specialized art of precious\nstone cutting. Mr. Marleau is a na\ntive of Montreal, Canada, and resided\nin Los Angeles, California, where he\nwas in business, for thirty-two years.\nHe served his apprenticeship in New\nYork City under the masters of his\nprofession.\nSince coming here, about one year\nago, Mr. Marleau has expressed his\ntalent and genius in developing into\nLLOYD HENNING\nMayor of Holbrook\nthe finest jewelry, along such a high\nplane as hitherto been unknown, the\ncutting, polishing, mounting and\nmanufacturing of petrified wood\njewelry, taken from our own world\nfamed Petrified Forest of Arizona.\nAlong this line Mr. Marleau has man\nufactured, and has on hand for sale,\nalmost any form conceivable of\njewelry utilizing this stone (for pe\ntrified wood IS stone) in a bewilder\ning array, of the most exquisite and\nunusual shapes, bringing into play\nhis remarkable genius and years of\nexperience. In other words, Mr. Mar\nleau makes up to order, to suit the\nindividual purchaser, or has on hand\ndifferent displays of work done in\npetrified wood, al >ng the same high\nclass workmanship as is usually to\nbe found only in the precious stones.\nMr. Marleau states that there are\nfive stages of petrification, and that\neach stage offers a different color,\nand that the combination of these dif\nferent stages offers color schemes in\ncombinations not found in any other\nstone. All of these, 'however, take\na very high polish in the hands of\nan expert who knows the chemical\nreaction necessary to bring out the\nhigh lustre such as is d'rne with pre\ncious stones. Mr. Mar'eau has built\nup a business along this line all over\nthe United States, and mail orders\nor purchases by correspondence is\ngiven the same careful and artistic\nattention as if the customer made a\nselection here in his shop. Taken\nall in all Mr. Marleau\u2019s slogan \u201cPet\nrified wood jewelry, the gift unique\u201d\nis a most apt one and true to the\nletter, as no two pieces of petrified\nwood stone are alike in coloring and\nshades \u2014they may be alike in shape,\nbut never in appearance\u2014-so that,\neach piece of jewelry made from this\nis an exclusive design, and has an\nintrinsic value all its own.\nMr. Marleau is a booster for this\n(Continued on next Section)","height":"24519","width":"16917"}}
